Step 2. Read in lobster file + make it tidy

lobster_raw <- read_csv("lobster_abundance_sbc_lter.csv", na = "-99999")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   YEAR = col_double(),
##   MONTH = col_double(),
##   DATE = col_date(format = ""),
##   SITE = col_character(),
##   TRANSECT = col_double(),
##   REPLICATE = col_character(),
##   SIZE_MM = col_double(),
##   COUNT = col_double(),
##   NUM_AO = col_double(),
##   AREA = col_double()
## )
lobster_tidy <- lobster_raw %>% 
  clean_names() %>%
  tidyr::uncount(count) %>% 
  select(year:size_mm)

Potential Histogram

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_histogram(data = transform(lobster_tidy, site = NULL), binwidth = 1, fill = "gray90") + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1,
                 aes(fill = site),
                 show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~site)+
  theme_light()+
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Lobster Count",
       title = "MAKE A REALLY AWESOME COOL TITLE")

Results B.

Visually explore lobster size distribution shifts Compare lobster sizes in 2012 and 2018

lobster_12_18 <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(year %in% c(2012, 2018))

Visually explore the size distributions for lobsters observed at the 5 different sites in 2012, and in 2018 (i.e.you will have a total of 10 size distributions shown: for each of the 5 sites, one for 2012 and one for 2018).

lobster_size <- lobster_12_18 %>% 
  select(year, site, size_mm)
ggplot(lobster_size, aes(x = size_mm, y = site)) +
  geom_density_ridges(aes(fill = site),
                      show.legend = FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(30, 135),
                     expand = c(0,0)) +
  theme_light()+
  labs(x = "Lobster Size (mm)",
       y = "Site",
       title = "WRITE A TOTALLY RADTASTIC TITLE")
